[Zamboanga City]]''<ref name=\"MB-CovidZamboangaCity\">{{cite news |last1=Lacson |first1=Nonoy |title=First COVID-19 patient confirmed in Zamboanga City |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/25/first-covid-19-patient-confirmed-in-zamboanga-city/ |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Zamboanga del Sur]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Zamboanga del Sur reports first two COVID-19 cases |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/regional/2020/3/30/Zamboanga-del-Sur-first-coronavirus-cases.html |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=CNN Philippine |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Northern Mindanao]] (Region X)\n**''[[Cagayan de Oro]]''<ref>{{cite news |title=Calamba, Cagayan de Oro report first cases of COVID-19 |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/25/Philippines-cities-provinces-first-cases-COVID-19.html?fbclid=IwAR2sGxWcoZqVAzYGxaAjFYQl51801JWiKdTkNPwFezr4oVuexiqQ2yNin1k |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n**''[[Iligan]]''<ref>{{cite news |title=Iligan City records 1st COVID-19 case |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/25/iligan-city-records-1st-covid-19-case/ |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Lanao del Norte]]<ref name=\"Inquirer-CovidLanaoDelNorte\">{{cite news |last1=Umel |first1=Richel |title=Entire village in Lanao Norte on lockdown after resident tests positive for COVID-19 |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1251150/entire-village-in-lanao-norte-on-lockdown-after-resident-tests-positive-for-covid-19 |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 30, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n**[[Misamis Occidental]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Mayor confirms first COVID-19 case in Ozamiz City |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1250574/mayor-confirms-first-covid-19-case-in-ozamiz-city |accessdate=April 3, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Davao Region]] (Region XI)\n**''[[Davao City]]''<ref name=\"MB-CovidDavaoCity\">{{cite news |title=2 COVID-19 cases confirmed in Davao City |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/22/2-covid-19-cases-confirmed-in-davao-city/ |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MB-CovidDavaoRegion\" />\n**[[Davao de Oro]]<ref name=\"MB-CovidDavaoRegion\">{{cite news |last1=Valdez |first1=Warren |title=Davao Region COVID-19 Update: 50 positive cases; six fatalities |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/31/davao-region-covid-19-update-50-positive-cases-six-fatalities/ |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Davao del Norte]]<ref name=\"MB-CovidDavaoRegion\" />\n**[[Davao del Sur]]<ref name=\"MB-CovidDavaoRegion\" />\n**[[Davao Oriental]]<ref name=\"MB-CovidDavaoRegion\" />\n*[[Soccsksargen]] (Region XII)\n**[[South Cotabato]]<ref name=\"PNAGovPH-CovidSouthCotabato\">{{cite news |last1=Osano |first1=Roel |title=South Cotabato confirms 1st positive Covid-19 case |url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1098326 |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=Philippine News Agency |date=March 31, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n**[[Sultan Kudarat]]<ref>{{cite news |title=With confirmed COVID-19 case, Sultan Kudarat to impose lockdown, curfew |url=https://www.mindanews.com/top-stories/2020/03/with-confirmed-covid-19-case-sultan-kudarat-to-impose-lockdown-curfew/ |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=MindaNews |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Bangsamoro]] (BARMM)\n**''[[Cotabato City]]''<ref name=\"PIAGovPH-CovidCotabatoCity\">{{cite news |title=Cotabato City records first COVID 19 case in R12 |url=https://pia.gov.ph/news/articles/1036522 |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=Philippine Information Agency |agency=PIA Cotabato City |date=March 18, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n**[[Lanao del Sur]]<ref name=\"ABS-CBN-CovidLanaoDelSur\">{{cite news |last1=Butardo |first1=Maria Cecilia |title=COVID-19 positive patient dies in Lanao del Sur |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/17/20/covid-19-positive-patient-dies-in-lanao-del-sur |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 17, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n;COVID-19-free regions\n*[[Caraga Region]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Caraga readies contingency plan for COVID-19 worst-case scenario |url=https://pia.gov.ph/news/articles/1037536 |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |agency=Philippine Information Agency |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> (Region XIII)\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Philippines}}\n* [[2009 flu pandemic in the Philippines]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.covid19.gov.ph/ Philippine Government's Online Portal for the COVID-19 pandemic].\n* [https://ncovtracker.doh.gov.ph/ COVID-19 case and situation tracker] by the [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]]\n* [https://corona.arrangy.com Worldwide Coronavirus Map, confirmed Cases] \u2013 Map the route paths of coronavirus confirmed cases.\n* [https://endcov.ph/dashboard/ University of the Philippines COVID-19 case tracker]\n* [https://covid19ph.com/ Unofficial COVID-19 Philippines data and case tracker]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\n{{Rodrigo Duterte}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Philippines]]\n[[Category:2020 disasters in the Philippines|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Philippines]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines| ]]\n", "name_user": "PatTag2659", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTesting facilities", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_the_Philippines"}
{"title_page": "Lovie Austin", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Lovie Austin\n| image               = Lovie_Austin.jpg\n| caption             = \n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name          = Cora Taylor\n| alias               = Cora Calhoun<br>Cora Austin\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1887|9|19|mf=y}}\n| birth_place              = [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]], United States\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|1972|7|8|1887|9|19|mf=y}}\n| death_place          = [[Chicago, Illinois]], United States\n| instrument          = Piano\n| genre               = [[Jazz]], [[Jazz blues]]\n| occupation          = Musician<br/>Composer<br/>Bandleader\n| years_active        = 1920s&ndash;1972\n| label               = [[Paramount Records|Paramount]]}}\n\n'''Cora''' \"'''Lovie'''\" '''Austin''' (September 19, 1887 \u2013 July 8, 1972)<ref name=\"bare\"/><ref>{{Cite book|title = Chicago Jazz: A Cultural History, 1904-1930|last = Kenney|first = William Holland|publisher = Oxford Paperbacks|date = May 13, 1993|isbn = |location = |pages = }}</ref> was an American [[Chicago]] bandleader, session musician, composer, singer, and arranger during the 1920s [[Classic female blues|classic blues]] era.<ref name=\"RCJE\">{{Cite book\n | last = Cook\n | first = Richard\n | author-link = \n | year = 2005\n | title = Richard Cook's Jazz Encyclopedia\n | publisher = Penguin Books\n | location = London\n | isbn = 0-141-00646-3\n | pages = 24\n}}</ref> She and [[Lil Hardin Armstrong]] are often ranked as two of the best female [[jazz blues]] piano players of the period.<ref name=\"santelli\">Santelli, Robert. ''The Big Book of Blues'', Penguin Books, pg. 20, (2001); {{ISBN|0-14-100145-3}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nShe was born '''Cora Taylor''' in [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]].<ref name=\"bare\">{{cite book| first1= Bob| last1= Eagle| first2= Eric S.| last2= LeBlanc| year= 2013| title= Blues - A Regional Experience| publisher= Praeger Publishers| location= Santa Barbara| pages=50 | isbn= 978-0313344237}}</ref>  Lovie grew up with eight brothers and sisters.<ref>{{Cite web|title = William Austin|url = http://www.geni.com/people/William-Austin/4377581528570073115|website = geni_family_tree|accessdate = 2015-10-14}}</ref> She took the name '''Cora Calhoun''' in her teens from an early marriage;<ref name=\"bare\"/> she was married for a short time to a movie house operator in Detroit and then later married a vaudeville performer, Phillip Austin.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title = Black Women of the Harlem Renaissance Era|last = Smith|first = Jessie Carney|publisher = Rowman and Littlefield|year = |isbn = |location = |pages = }}</ref>  She studied music theory at [[Roger Williams University]] and [[Knoxville College]] in [[Knoxville, Tennessee]] which was uncommon for African American woman and jazz musicians alike during the time.<ref name=\"santelli\"/>\n\nIn 1923, Lovie Austin decided to make [[Chicago]] her home, and she lived and worked there for the rest of her life. She was often seen racing around town in her [[Stutz Bearcat]] with leopard skin upholstery, dressed to the teeth. Her early career was in [[vaudeville]], where she played piano and performed in variety acts.<ref>Zieff, Bob. ''Lovie Austin.'' in Kernfeld, Barry, ed., ''The New Grove Dictionary of Jazz'', 2nd Edition, Vol. 1. London: MacMillan, p. 93 (2002).<!-- ISBN needed --></ref> Accompanying blues singers was Lovie's specialty, and can be heard on recordings by [[Ma Rainey]] (\"Moonshine Blues), [[Ida Cox]] (\"[[Wild Women Don't Have the Blues]]\"), [[Ethel Waters]] (\"Craving Blues\"), and [[Alberta Hunter]] (\"Sad 'n' Lonely Blues\").<ref>Laird, Ross, ''Moanin' Low: A Discography of Female Popular Vocal Recordings, 1920-1933'', Greenwood Press, p. 110 (1996); {{ISBN|0-313-29241-8}}]</ref>\n\nShe led her own band, the Blues Serenaders, which usually included trumpeters [[Tommy Ladnier]], [[Bob Shoffner]], [[Natty Dominique]], or [[Shirley Clay]] on cornet, [[Kid Ory]] or [[Albert Wynn]] on trombone, and [[Jimmy O'Bryant]] or [[Johnny Dodds]] on clarinet, along with banjo and occasional drums. The Blues Serenaders developed their own unique sound within the jazz genre. They strayed away from the typical jazz band paradigm.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Chicago Jazz: A Cultural History, 1904-1930|last = William|first = Kenney|publisher = Oxford Paperbacks|year = |isbn = |location = |pages = }}</ref> Austin worked with many other top jazz musicians of the 1920s, including [[Louis Armstrong]], with whom she worked on the song \"Heebie Jeebies\". Austin's skills as songwriter can be heard in the classic \"[[Downhearted Blues|Down Hearted Blues]]\", a tune she co-wrote with Alberta Hunter. The lament of a woman with a broken heart, the song describes how the man she loved \"wrecked her life.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Bessie Smith - Downhearted Blues Lyrics {{!}} SongMeanings|url = http://songmeanings.com/songs/view/3530822107858830863/|website = SongMeanings|accessdate = 2015-10-14}}</ref> Singer [[Bessie Smith]] turned the song into a hit in 1923.<ref>Cullen, Frank. Vaudeville, ''Old and New: An Encyclopedia of Variety Performers in America'', Routledge, p. 48 (2006); {{ISBN|0-415-93853-8}}</ref> Austin was also a session musician for [[Paramount Records]]. Austin and the Blues Serenaders recorded with Paramount Records during their temporary shift from New York to Chicago in 1923.<ref>{{Cite web|title = ParamountsHome.Org -  Wabash Rag: Paramount's Chicago Studios by Alex Van Der Tuuk|url = http://paramountshome.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=97:-wabash-rag-paramounts-chicago-studios-by-alex-van-der-tuuk&catid=46:new-york-recording-laboratoriesdiscography&Itemid=54|website = paramountshome.org|accessdate = 2015-10-14}}</ref>\n\nWhen the classic blues craze began to wane in the early 1930s, Austin settled into the position of musical director for the [[Monogram Theater]], at 3453 South State Street in Chicago where all the [[T.O.B.A.]] acts played. She worked there for 20 years. During wartime, many jazz musicians had to find other forms of work to support themselves and Austin was reported to be working as a security guard at a defense plant. After [[World War II]] she became a pianist at Jimmy Payne's Dancing School at Penthouse Studios, and performed and recorded occasionally.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Lovie Austin|url = https://syncopatedtimes.com/lovie-austin-1897-1972/|website = Red Hot Jazz Archive|accessdate = 2020-04-04}}</ref> In 1961 as interest in her early career grew she made a significant recording with Alberta Hunter in Chicago.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Lovie Austin:The Hidden Blues Queen who Inspired Swing Kingmakers|url = https://syncopatedtimes.com/lovie-austin-the-hidden-blues-queen-who-inspired-swing-kingmakers/|website = The Syncopated Times|accessdate = 2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nAustin died on July 8, 1972 in Chicago.<ref name=\"bare\"/>\n\n== Influence ==\n[[Mary Lou Williams]], a pianist born in Atlanta, Georgia,<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.biography.com/people/mary-lou-williams-9532632|title = Mary Lou Williams Biography|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> claims that Lovie Austin is her greatest influence. Williams refers to Austin as, \"a fabulous woman and a fabulous musician too. I don't believe there's a woman around now who could compete with her. She was a greater talent than many of the men of this period.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Lovie Austin @ All About Jazz|url = http://musicians.allaboutjazz.com/index_new.php?url=lovieaustin&&width=1280|website = All About Jazz|accessdate = 2015-10-14}}</ref> With her performances and compositions, Lovie enriched the lives of black female artists during the Harlem Renaissance.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Discography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Genre\n!Label\n|-\n|1994\n|''1924-1926''\n|Jazz blues\n|Classic\n|- \n|1961\n|''Alberta Hunter with Lovie Austin's Blues Serenaders''\n|Jazz\n|Allegro Corporation \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Austin, Lovie}}\n[[Category:1887 births]]\n[[Category:1972 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Chattanooga, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:American female jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:Vaudeville performers]]\n[[Category:American blues pianists]]\n[[Category:Dixieland pianists]]\n[[Category:Paramount Records artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women pianists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American pianists]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from Tennessee]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Lovie Austin\n| image               = Lovie_Austin.jpg\n| caption             = \n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name          = Cora Taylor\n| alias               = Cora Calhoun<br>Cora Austin\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1887|9|19|mf=y}}\n| birth_place              = [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]], United States\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|1972|7|8|1887|9|19|mf=y}}\n| death_place          = [[Chicago, Illinois]], United States\n| instrument          = Piano\n| genre               = [[Jazz]], [[Jazz blues]]\n| occupation          = Musician<br/>Composer<br/>Bandleader\n| years_active        = 1920s&ndash;1972\n| label               = [[Paramount Records|Paramount]]}}\n\n'''Cora''' \"'''Lovie'''\" '''Austin''' (September 19, 1887 \u2013 July 8, 1972)<ref name=\"bare\"/><ref>{{Cite book|title = Chicago Jazz: A Cultural History, 1904-1930|last = Kenney|first = William Holland|publisher = Oxford Paperbacks|date = May 13, 1993|isbn = |location = |pages = }}</ref> was an American [[Chicago]] bandleader, session musician, composer, singer, and arranger during the 1920s [[Classic female blues|classic blues]] era.<ref name=\"RCJE\">{{Cite book\n | last = Cook\n | first = Richard\n | author-link = \n | year = 2005\n | title = Richard Cook's Jazz Encyclopedia\n | publisher = Penguin Books\n | location = London\n | isbn = 0-141-00646-3\n | pages = 24\n}}</ref> She and [[Lil Hardin Armstrong]] are often ranked as two of the best female [[jazz blues]] piano players of the period.<ref name=\"santelli\">Santelli, Robert. ''The Big Book of Blues'', Penguin Books, pg. 20, (2001); {{ISBN|0-14-100145-3}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nShe was born '''Cora Taylor''' in [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]].<ref name=\"bare\">{{cite book| first1= Bob| last1= Eagle| first2= Eric S.| last2= LeBlanc| year= 2013| title= Blues - A Regional Experience| publisher= Praeger Publishers| location= Santa Barbara| pages=50 | isbn= 978-0313344237}}</ref>  Lovie grew up with eight brothers and sisters.<ref>{{Cite web|title = William Austin|url = http://www.geni.com/people/William-Austin/4377581528570073115|website = geni_family_tree|accessdate = 2015-10-14}}</ref> She took the name '''Cora Calhoun''' in her teens from an early marriage;<ref name=\"bare\"/> she was married for a short time to a movie house operator in Detroit and then later married a vaudeville performer, Phillip Austin.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title = Black Women of the Harlem Renaissance Era|last = Smith|first = Jessie Carney|publisher = Rowman and Littlefield|year = |isbn = |location = |pages = }}</ref>  She studied music theory at [[Roger Williams University]] and [[Knoxville College]] in [[Knoxville, Tennessee]] which was uncommon for African American woman and jazz musicians alike during the time.<ref name=\"santelli\"/>\n\nIn 1923, Lovie Austin decided to make [[Chicago]] her home, and she lived and worked there for the rest of her life. She was often seen racing around town in her [[Stutz Bearcat]] with leopard skin upholstery, dressed to the teeth. Her early career was in [[vaudeville]], where she played piano and performed in variety acts.<ref>Zieff, Bob. ''Lovie Austin.'' in Kernfeld, Barry, ed., ''The New Grove Dictionary of Jazz'', 2nd Edition, Vol. 1. London: MacMillan, p. 93 (2002).<!-- ISBN needed --></ref> Accompanying blues singers was Lovie's specialty, and can be heard on recordings by [[Ma Rainey]] (\"Moonshine Blues), [[Ida Cox]] (\"[[Wild Women Don't Have the Blues]]\"), [[Ethel Waters]] (\"Craving Blues\"), and [[Alberta Hunter]] (\"Sad 'n' Lonely Blues\").<ref>Laird, Ross, ''Moanin' Low: A Discography of Female Popular Vocal Recordings, 1920-1933'', Greenwood Press, p. 110 (1996); {{ISBN|0-313-29241-8}}]</ref>\n\nShe led her own band, the Blues Serenaders, which usually included trumpeters [[Tommy Ladnier]], [[Bob Shoffner]], [[Natty Dominique]], or [[Shirley Clay]] on cornet, [[Kid Ory]] or [[Albert Wynn]] on trombone, and [[Jimmy O'Bryant]] or [[Johnny Dodds]] on clarinet, along with banjo and occasional drums. The Blues Serenaders developed their own unique sound within the jazz genre. They strayed away from the typical jazz band paradigm.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Chicago Jazz: A Cultural History, 1904-1930|last = William|first = Kenney|publisher = Oxford Paperbacks|year = |isbn = |location = |pages = }}</ref> Austin worked with many other top jazz musicians of the 1920s, including [[Louis Armstrong]], with whom she worked on the song \"Heebie Jeebies\". Austin's skills as songwriter can be heard in the classic \"[[Downhearted Blues|Down Hearted Blues]]\", a tune she co-wrote with Alberta Hunter. The lament of a woman with a broken heart, the song describes how the man she loved \"wrecked her life.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Bessie Smith - Downhearted Blues Lyrics {{!}} SongMeanings|url = http://songmeanings.com/songs/view/3530822107858830863/|website = SongMeanings|accessdate = 2015-10-14}}</ref> Singer [[Bessie Smith]] turned the song into a hit in 1923.<ref>Cullen, Frank. Vaudeville, ''Old and New: An Encyclopedia of Variety Performers in America'', Routledge, p. 48 (2006); {{ISBN|0-415-93853-8}}</ref> Austin was also a session musician for [[Paramount Records]]. Austin and the Blues Serenaders recorded with Paramount Records during their temporary shift from New York to Chicago in 1923.<ref>{{Cite web|title = ParamountsHome.Org -  Wabash Rag: Paramount's Chicago Studios by Alex Van Der Tuuk|url = http://paramountshome.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=97:-wabash-rag-paramounts-chicago-studios-by-alex-van-der-tuuk&catid=46:new-york-recording-laboratoriesdiscography&Itemid=54|website = paramountshome.org|accessdate = 2015-10-14}}</ref>\n\nWhen the classic blues craze began to wane in the early 1930s, Austin settled into the position of musical director for the [[Monogram Theater]], at 3453 South State Street in Chicago where all the [[T.O.B.A.]] acts played. She worked there for 20 years. During wartime, many jazz musicians had to find other forms of work to support themselves and Austin was reported to be working as a security guard at a defense plant. After [[World War II]] she became a pianist at Jimmy Payne's Dancing School at Penthouse Studios, and performed and recorded occasionally.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Lovie Austin|url = https://syncopatedtimes.com/lovie-austin-1897-1972/|website = Red Hot Jazz Archive|accessdate = 2020-04-04}}</ref> In 1961 as interest in her early career grew made a significant recording with Alberta Hunter in Chicago.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Lovie Austin:The Hidden Blues Queen who Inspired Swing Kingmakers|url = https://syncopatedtimes.com/lovie-austin-the-hidden-blues-queen-who-inspired-swing-kingmakers/|website = The Syncopated Times|accessdate = 2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nAustin died on July 8, 1972 in Chicago.<ref name=\"bare\"/>\n\n== Influence ==\n[[Mary Lou Williams]], a pianist born in Atlanta, Georgia,<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.biography.com/people/mary-lou-williams-9532632|title = Mary Lou Williams Biography|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> claims that Lovie Austin is her greatest influence. Williams refers to Austin as, \"a fabulous woman and a fabulous musician too. I don't believe there's a woman around now who could compete with her. She was a greater talent than many of the men of this period.\"<ref>{{Cite web|title = Lovie Austin @ All About Jazz|url = http://musicians.allaboutjazz.com/index_new.php?url=lovieaustin&&width=1280|website = All About Jazz|accessdate = 2015-10-14}}</ref> With her performances and compositions, Lovie enriched the lives of black female artists during the Harlem Renaissance.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Discography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Genre\n!Label\n|-\n|1994\n|''1924-1926''\n|Jazz blues\n|Classic\n|- \n|1961\n|''Alberta Hunter with Lovie Austin's Blues Serenaders''\n|Jazz\n|Allegro Corporation \n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Austin, Lovie}}\n[[Category:1887 births]]\n[[Category:1972 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Chattanooga, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:American female jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:Vaudeville performers]]\n[[Category:American blues pianists]]\n[[Category:Dixieland pianists]]\n[[Category:Paramount Records artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women pianists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American pianists]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from Tennessee]]\n", "name_user": "Ghmyrtle", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife and career", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lovie_Austin"}
